Heard distinctive and vaguely familiar (out of place/mind) short cooing (initially 3-4 bouts, and another after a long pause) coming from brushy area adjacent Hilda Rd feeders and went and located the bird sitting under the canopy of a pine tree.. Larger/chunkier than MODO. Distant black “collar” noted with long squared tail, black base (one quarter) to tail, 3/4 whitish to the tip of undertail, and grey (not white per African Collared) undertail coverts. Later confirmed the song lacked the long, drawn-out rolling "r" aspect towards the end that is a hallmark of African Collard Dove song.

Observation Details: Someone is feeding feral cats and wild birds behind the bushes between Walmart and Home Depot, and there was a flock of Eurasian Collared-Doves feeding on what appeared to be cracked corn and mixed seed. I parked my car and counted the birds, and when I opened the door to get out and take photos, all of the doves spooked and flew up into the trees. I took a few photos of them in the trees and then they all took off and flew in the direction of the Home Depot parking lot. I drove around to that spot and found most of them -- some were perched on a wire (photo attached) and others were in the trees.

Two adult birds flew past together when I was walking towards the entrance of the reserve. While overlooking Laguna del río Viejo two adult birds flew in and landed in the tree growing in the centre of the laguna. When I was walking from Laguna del río Viejo towards río Viejo I saw nine adult bird fly past, all coming from the City of Málaga towards the centre of the reserve. They were seen in four groups of two, three, one and three. At Laguna Grande I found, as usual, this species again. I counted fourteen adult birds perched in the dead, but standing, trees to the left of the laguna when looking at it from the hide. As I left the hide an adult bird obligingly perched on the hide fence and I was able to obtain very good photographs.  Photograph.  28 adults.

Media notes: typical Eurasian
Observation Details: Usual large concentration at the Equestrian Center - viewable from the horse path along the LA River west of BD park. Single leucistic type that resembles what is often thought to be domestic "African" Barbary/Ringed Turtle Dove with strikingly pale frosty plumage and primaries. However, it has dark outer webs of outer rectrices and grayish undertail coverts (although slightly paler than typical Eurasian). Presumably a not too uncommon Leucistic Eurasian Collared Dove or perhaps a Eurasian with distant hybrid genes.

Observation Details: *Rare. Previously reported by several starting 6/22. Foraging alone on the lawn at the NW end of Pier 63 (about 23rd St.) just across the path from the flower beds where it was first reported. A robust, light brown to cream-colored dove, a little smaller than a pigeon, with a black tips of the folded wings, no spots, square tail, black crescent mark around the back and sides of the neck (the part on the back of the neck was not visible in some postures and light but very obvious at other times). I first saw it on the grass beyond a fence along the path,with benches on the path side, the nearest bench to the bird was occupied. After spotting the bird and having trouble photographing it, I circled around the far end of the fence and settled under a tree on a slight rise about 30 feet from the bird, who took no special notice of me and it eventually walked to within 8 feet of where I sat (and then away and back again). So we're not talking about a very skittish bird. I saw no bands or tags on the bird. It puffed up a couple of times to see off a robin and a fledgling starling. I noticed that adult starlings in the area nearby kept their distance, However, the dove walked rapidly away from two House Finches that flew in near it, and eventually flushed to the low branches of a small conifer behind me after a group of five House sparrows came and started dust-bathing a few feet from it. I think maybe it doesn't like small active birds. After flying to the tree (and its wing sounds were like a Mourning Dove's, perhaps a little higher-pitched) the bird began to preen, and then moved farther back into the branches. I went for a walk around the flower beds and the native plant garden to the north, and when I returned, the dove was back on the grass in the same area.

A photo below shows an especially pale dove walking on the ground.  It is not too uncommon to see Eurasian Collared-Doves much lighter in color than their compatriots.  This bird seemed especially so, particularly in the head color.  It also looks like the bird has white undertail coverts instead of gray.  Pale body color, pale brown primaries, and white undertail coverts could suggest Ringed Turtle-Dove (Domestic African Collared-Dove).  My attention was diverted momentarily and the bird flew off without me seeing the outer web under the bird’s tail.  A Eurasian Collared-Dove would show a black outer web, while a Turtle-Dove would have white.  For now, I am listing today’s bird as just a very light Eurasian Collared-Dove.

*High count (yet still conservative), and likely a record for Cook County. I originally counted 20+ birds scattered across multiple areas in the neighborhood southwest of the WWDO feeder (WWDO was the target for today). After an unsuccessful visit to the feeder, I went back to the same area in which I counted 27 doves in the same alley. This lead me to scratch my original count given the fact that most, if not all of these individuals would already have been counted. I then located two other separate pairs leading me to a final total of 31. I believe the main group of birds were in the alley between Parkside and Major.

Known bird here-- This Dove acting very much like the White-Winged Dove that was seen at Rondeau Provincial Park for several years. The White Winged  spent some of it's time on the car parked in the driveway taking nesting material and piling it on the rear windshield wiper. Today the Eurasian when arriving at the Truck spent some time moving twigs that where already present in the cowl below the wipers. Perhaps building a nest for it's reflection????

Observation Details: Not long after stepping outside, a SSHA came flying in and spooked the ECDO and NOFL. One of the doves struggled to escape and crash landed into the backyard. It began hopping up and down, trying to get back into the air, but failed. The hawk flew off to the south side of town. I let the dove be as it rested to regain its strength since it seemed fine. A few minutes later, I found the dove being attacked by a group of four stray kittens that we've been feeding for a while, as they began vigorously plucking it. I immediately took the bird and checked to see if it was suitable enough to fly yet. It was bleeding from the bill, but it didn't appear to be broken. The only obvious feathers missing were parts of the tail. I set it down on the bar of a swing set safe from the cats' reach. Within minutes, it was fully rested and had already flew off to a nearby tree with ease.

Media notes: Leucistic type that resembles "African" Barbary/Ringed Turtle Dove with strikingly pale plumage and primaries but dark outer web of outer rectrices
Observation Details: Usual large concentration at the Equestrian Center - viewable from the horse path along the LA River west of BD park. Single leucistic type that resembles what is often thought to be domestic "African" Barbary/Ringed Turtle Dove with strikingly pale frosty plumage and primaries. However, it has dark outer webs of outer rectrices and grayish undertail coverts (although slightly paler than typical Eurasian). Presumably a not too uncommon Leucistic Eurasian Collared Dove or perhaps a Eurasian with distant hybrid genes.

Larger Dove than Mourning, mostly light gray all over with light brown back, darker gray primaries, long tail with square end and black half collar on nape.  Birds calling as I was observing.  Larger size, square tail, black half collar on nape, lighter coloration and lower  pitched call eliminates MODO.  Photos and Audio to follow.

Observation Details: Pleasant surprise while driving along Whitehead Avenue.  Larger and somewhat paler than Mourning Dove.  Rounded tail with broad white terminal band broken by middle retrices.  Compared to African Collared-Dove (Ringed Turtle-Dove), which has also been reported in our area, the Eurasian Collared-Dove exhibited darker primaries contrasting with the rest of the wings, gray undertail coverts (vs. white), and dark undertail webbing extending farther down the tail.  Sang a few times (repeated coo-COOO-coo) and several times emitted a harsh call reminiscent of a crow or catbird scold call.  Sometimes gave chase to the Mourning Doves.  The EC Dove was repeatedly seen along Whitehead Avenue near Ria Mar restaurant between Prentice Avenue to the north and the fenced green space along Kamm Avenue to the south.  Also seen along Robert Street and Schack Avenue, Kathryn Street, and the parking lot behind the Gold Star Bar.  Seen with Tom G., Patrick, and Craig.  Edit: While the identity of this bird is not in doubt, perhaps its provenance is after review of the photos and discussion with others.  All of the retrices, particularly the middle two, and some of the primaries show wear.  The tail on the perched bird is not square, but rather two-pronged.  Whether this wear is attributable to recent captivity or inclement weather (periods of heavy rain April 29), is better answered by those experienced in such matters.  In favor of a wild origin, I have added a photo that shows the legs are not banded.  Also, as I and others followed the bird, it did not permit close approach.  This is a NJ review list species, and I will provide supporting details to NJBRC.
